5000|$|In January 1980 Abolhassan Banisadr, {{an adviser}} to Khomeini, was elected {{president}} of Iran. He was opposed by the more radical <b>Islamic</b> <b>Republic</b> <b>party,</b> who controlled the parliament, having won the first parliamentary election of March-May 1980. Banisadr was compelled to accept an IRP-oriented prime minister, Mohammad-Ali Rajai, he declared [...] "incompetent." [...] Both Banisadr and the IRP were supported by Khomeini.|$|E
50|$|Jaleleddin Farsi (جلال‌الدین فارسی in Persian), born as Hekmatollah Baaraan-Cheshmeh (حکمت الله باران چشمه in Persian), was {{the presidential}} {{candidate}} for the <b>Islamic</b> <b>Republic</b> <b>Party</b> in the first presidential election in Iran. He was chosen because Ayatollah Khomeini had personally forbidden the party from running Mohammad Beheshti, a cleric, for president. Farsi was later banned by the order of Ayatollah Khomeini, because his family had migrated from Herat, Afghanistan, {{even though he was}} born in Mashhad.|$|E
